{{Politics of the Republic of Macedonia}}
The [[Republic of Macedonia]] is a signatory to the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] and the U.N. Geneva [[Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees|Convention relating to the Status of Refugees]] and [[United Nations Convention Against Torture|Convention against Torture]], and the Macedonian Constitution guarantees basic human rights to all citizens.
There do however continue to be problems with [[human rights]]. According to human rights organisations, in 2003 there were suspected extrajudicial executions, threats and intimidation against human rights activists and anti-regime journalists and allegations of [[torture]] by the police.<ref>[http://web.amnesty.org/report2003/mkd-summary-eng Amnesty International - Summary - Macedonia]</ref><ref name="hrw2006">[https://www.hrw.org/campaigns/macedonia/ Human Rights Watch - Campaigns - Conflict in Macedonia]</ref>
The country also has issues with the human rights of [[ethnic minorities]], such as [[Albanians in the Republic of Macedonia|Albanians]], [[Bulgarians]], [[Serbs]], [[Roma in Macedonia|Roma]], [[Turks_in_the_Republic_of_Macedonia|Turks]], [[Aromanians]], [[Greeks]] and [[Vlachs]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}{{specify|date=November 2013}}{{examples|date=November 2013}}
Although Albanians have since 2002 been allowed to study in Albanian, before graduating from university they are required to pass a test of their comprehension and use of the [[Macedonian language]].<ref name="hrw2001">[https://www.hrw.org/wr2k1/europe/macedonia.html Human Rights Watch - Macedonia]</ref>
==HRW and Helsinki Watch==
According to [[Human Rights Watch]], many former [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] citizens remain "effectively stateless"<ref name="hrw2001" /> as a result of a citizenship law drafted after Macedonia's secession from the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]].
Conflict between ethnic Albanian secesionists and the Macedonian government has resulted in serious violations of [[human rights]] on both sides.<ref name="hrw2006" />
According to the [[International Helsinki Federation for Human Rights]], the following human rights abuses have been reported:<ref name="Helsinki">[http://www.mhc.org.mk/search_result.asp?path=/eng/a_izveshtai/a_drugi_i_03_2006_1.htm&search=Albanians Country Reports on Human Rights Practices - 2005 (MHC)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311004230/http://www.mhc.org.mk/search_result.asp?path=%2Feng%2Fa_izveshtai%2Fa_drugi_i_03_2006_1.htm&search=Albanians |date=2007-03-11 }}</ref>{{Citation broken|date=November 2013}}{{Failed verification|date=November 2013}}
* Police abuse of suspects, particularly during initial arrest and detention * Police harassment of ethnic minorities, particularly Roma * Impunity and corruption in the police force * Political pressure on the judiciary * Societal violence and discrimination against women, children and ethnic minorities, particularly Roma * Trafficking in women and girls for sexual exploitation * Government interference with union activity
