'''Rublon''' is a [[two-factor authentication]] system that acts as an additional security layer which protects the [[password]]-based [[login]] process to [[web application]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.institutionalinvestor.com/blogarticle/3223444/Blog/Getting-Past-Passwords-and-a-Secure-Future.html |title=Getting Past Passwords and a Secure Future |author=Jeff Kutler |publisher=Institutional Investor |date=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpcentral.com/say-hello-rublon-new-way-stay-secure-your-windows-phone |title=Say hello to Rublon; a new way to stay secure with your Windows Phone |author=Michael Archambault |publisher=Windows Phone Central |date=September 13, 2013}}</ref> A protected [[user (computing)|account]] can only be accessed by someone who enters the correct password and scans a [[QR code]] using the Rublon [[mobile app]], which holds the [[digital identity]] of the account's owner. In [[web browser]]s that have been previously defined as trusted, only the password is needed in order to sign into a protected account of any supported web application.
== Mobile app == Accounts can be protected by installing the Rublon mobile app, which is available for smartphones with [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[BlackBerry OS]], [[iOS]] and [[Windows Phone]]. The app is also used to define trusted browsers that make it possible to sign in using a password only. The app can be activated by providing an email address, which results in the creation of the user's digital identity using asymmetric cryptographic [[RSA (cryptosystem)|RSA]] keys.
== Supported web applications == Rublon protects the accounts of web applications that are integrated with its system. There are plugins for [[Magento]], [[PrestaShop]] and [[WordPress]], allowing administrators of websites based on these platforms to integrate them without programming.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpmayor.com/plugin-reviews/rublon-review/ |title=Rublon Review |author=Jean Galea |publisher=WPMayor |date=October 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpwhitesecurity.com/wordpress-plugins/rublon-invisible-two-factor-authentication-wordpress/ |title=Secure WordPress Login with Rublon Two-Factor Authentication |author=Robert Abela |publisher=WP White Security |date=December 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.net-security.org/review.php?id=318 |title=Two-factor authentication for WordPress using Rublon |author=Berislav Kucan |publisher=Help Net Security |date=February 28, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303105947/https://www.net-security.org/review.php?id=318 |archivedate=March 3, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Web application developers may use the [[Java (programming language)|Java]] and [[PHP]] [[Software development kit|SDKs]] to integrate Rublon with their services.
